Human Interest: Henry and Matthew find themselves needing to find a new housekeeper when Enid wins money on the premium bonds. Will they be able to agree on a suitable replacement?
Success Story: Matthew is delighted when Henry's successful younger brother Edward comes to stay. But will Henry be proud or envious of his sibling's achievements?
Rumpole and the Barrow Boy: Rumpole agrees to defend Nigel Timson when his insider trading case comes to trial. Elsewhere, Hilda becomes increasingly frustrated by Rumpole's lack of ambition.

Love And Marriage: Part 1: Jonathan and Mark take a couple back in time to help them understand what life would have been like had they not met each other 49 years earlier.

Love And Marriage: Part 2: Mark gives his friend a lesson about marriage that he hopes she will hold dear to her before marrying her fiancé Brad.

High Spirits: Cynical about Matthew and Fiona's belief in ghosts, Henry accepts the challenge to stay in a haunted, abandoned railway station overnight.
The Caretakers: Grandpa gets angry and moves out with Grandma after John suggests he take life a little easier.
The Shivaree: Olivia plans a wedding for a friend's daughter, but the city-bred financier objects to the proceedings, not really understanding the customs of the people of Walton's Mountain.
The Choice: John considers Jason's desire to study music a waste of time. Jason, however, is intent on following his dreams and tries to win a scholarship to the Klineberg Conservatory.
The Statue: Grandpa is the lucky winner of a raffle from Ike Godsey's store; however, Grandma's feelings are hurt when she sees the prize.
The Song: Ben's plan to win a girl's heart sends her into the arms of Jason.
The Woman: John and Olivia are preparing to celebrate their 20th wedding anniversary, and John-Boy begins to make plans with an older woman, whom he falls in love with.
The Venture: The family may lose its considerable investment in a new business when John is hospitalised with pneumonia.
The Sermon: When Walton Mountain's only schoolteacher and its minister suddenly decide to get married, John-Boy has to give the Sunday sermon.

U.N. the Night and the Music: Three UN delegates visit the camp and make a lasting impression. BJ has no time for visitors when his patient must lose his leg after gangrene sets in.
Strange Bedfellows: Charles' snoring is keeping Hawkeye and BJ awake at night but he refuses to discuss any suggestions. Colonel Potter discovers that his son-in-law has had an affair.
Say No More: General Collins refuses to accept responsibility for the war gaming which mortally wounded his son. Margaret develops laryngitis just before meeting her hero, Dr Steven Chesler.
Friends and Enemies: Colonel Potter must decide whether to blow the whistle on an old army friend, Colonel Woody Cooke, whose military mistakes are costing human lives.

An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
Code Name: Freak: Jonathan and Mark help Chris, a young genius, deal with college. Chris tries to accept his gift while the other kids find it hard to accept a classmate smarter than them.

Man To Man: A businessman would like to bridge the gap between himself and his son. Jonathan tries to make them live life to the fullest instead of letting their work lives take over.

A Song Of Songs: Gabe Wilson, an old friend of Mark's, tries to re-build his life after suffering a heart attack. He is reunited with his old flame but finds out she has changed.
A Night To Remember: Mark and Jonathan help two high school seniors, Danny and Kate, overcome their height issues as they get ready for prom.
No Beast So Fierce: James' budding friendship with another boy is jeopardised when he is caught mocking his new friend.
Stone Soup: Laura has a heart-to-heart talk with Willie about responsibility and being a good example to younger students. It's a talk Willie takes seriously and ends up saving Laura's life.
The Legacy: A present-day couple buy an antique folding-leaf table with a large 'I' branded on it and are curious to learn about its origins.
The Fighter: The Walton family befriends a young, Black preacher who wants to earn money for his own church by becoming a professional prizefighter.
The Prophecy: Thinking himself a failure compared to his more successful former classmates, John Walton is apprehensive and irritable as he contemplates his high school class' 25th reunion.
When a Child Is Born: A small statue in the chapel starts sweating, but Father Clifford is suspicious of the miracle. Niamh is calm about her impending baby, but Ambrose is terrified.
The Best Man: Dr Tom Gilder returns to Ormston when he is asked to be best man at a friend's wedding. Will the pull of village life convince him and his family to stay?
Stolen Lives: Rachel Gant has been committed to an asylum for the past 38 years. Her mother sees to her release only to discover the dark secrets that have been locked away.
Rumpole à la Carte: Rumpole agrees to defend an unlikeable restaurateur when a diner's meal is served to them with an additional, unwanted ingredient.
Germ Warfare: Hawkeye and Trapper move a North Korean POW patient into the Swamp and discover that he has the same blood type as Frank. They secretly plan to steal some of Frank's blood.
Dear Dad: It's Christmas and Hawkeye writes to his father describing his life at the 4077th. Amid the tension of the operating room he can still trade jokes with Trapper.
Edwina: A new nurse admits after her birthday party that no one has ever cared for her. The nurses refuse to date until their lonely colleague Edwina gets a date, so the men draw straws.
Love Story: Radar has received a 'Dear John' recording from his fiancee and becomes depressed. Hawkeye and Trapper decide what Radar needs is another girl.
Tuttle: To get some extra supplies for the local orphanage, Hawkeye and Trapper invent a fictional captain. The deception slowly grows until everyone believes Tuttle to be a real person.
The Ringbanger: Hawkeye and Trapper hit it off with a wounded Colonel, but when they discover his combat zeal is costing lives, they conspire to keep him from returning to the front line.
Sometimes You Hear the Bullet: Hawkeye's old friend appears at the 4077th. He's a soldier working on a book called You Never Hear the Bullet that hits a little too close to home for Hawkeye.
